******
[3] Newswire 15 May 2013
Date: Wed 15 May 2013
Source: The Columbus Dispatch, Reuters report [edited]
http://www.dispatch.com/content/stories/national_world/2013/05/15/sars-like-outbreak-has-spread-saudis-say.html


Saudi Arabia has confirmed 6 new cases of the SARS-like novel coronavirus in its Eastern province, state media reported on Monday [13 May 2013] and yesterday [14 May 2013], citing the health ministry.

It reported 4 new cases late Monday [13 May 2013] and 2 more late yesterday [14 May 2013]. In one of the new cases, the patient has been treated and released from the hospital, while in the others, the patients still were being treated, the Saudi Press Agency reported.

On Sunday [12 May 2013], Saudi Arabia said it had logged a total of 24 confirmed cases since the disease was identified last year [2012]; 15 ended in deaths. In its latest outbreak in the Eastern Region, it said it had 15 confirmed cases; 9 ended in deaths.

World Health Organization officials visiting Saudi Arabia to consult with authorities on the outbreak said on Sunday [12 May 2013] that it seemed likely the new virus could be passed between humans, but only after prolonged, close contact.

The new virus (nCoV) can cause coughing, fever, and pneumonia. A virus from the same family triggered the outbreak of severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) that swept the world after emerging in Asia and killed 775 people in 2003.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The WHO update confirms the newswire report of 4 additional cases of SARI attributable to infection with the nCoV in the Eastern Region of Saudi Arabia. The Saudi Arabian media release mentions an additional 2 cases not included in the WHO report, suggesting that these 2 additional cases involved healthcare workers. More information on the 2 new cases would be appreciated from knowledgeable sources.

With the additional 2 cases reported by the Saudi Arabian MOH the worldwide total of reported cases is now 40, with 20 deaths reported to date (15 May 2013).

For a map of Saudi Arabia, see http://healthmap.org/r/1HAJ. - Mod.MPP]
